            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 5,
            AppRoutes = """["/purchase-orders"]""",
            Tags = """["purchase-orders","procurement","freight","currency","incoterm","receiving"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## PO Shipping, Currency & Freight\n\nBeyond the parts and prices, a purchase order carries the commercial terms that determine landed cost: who pays the freight, in what currency the vendor quoted, and how much shipping actually cost when the goods arrive. This article covers the Shipping & Currency section on a PO and the freight-capture step inside receiving.\n\n### Shipping & Currency on a PO\n\nWhen you create a PO, a **Shipping & Currency** section has three fields. They start from your preferred vendor's defaults, and you can change them.\n\n- **Incoterm** — the shipping term (Incoterms 2020) that spells out who arranges and pays for transport, who insures, and when ownership passes. Examples: **EXW** (Ex Works — you arrange all transport), **FOB Origin** (you take ownership at the shipping point — the common US default), **FOB Destination** (the seller owns it until it reaches your dock), **CFR/CIF/CPT/CIP** (seller pays freight), **DAP/DPU** (delivered at place), and **DDP** (Delivered Duty Paid — seller pays freight and duty). Terms where the seller pays freight treat the freight as already included in the line price.\n- **Estimated Freight** — your expected shipping cost for the order. It feeds the order total (Subtotal + Estimated Freight = Total) and the vendor-minimum check.\n- **Quote Currency** — the currency the vendor quoted in (such as USD, EUR, GBP, CAD, MXN, JPY, or CNY, plus any currency your admin has added). Defaults to USD.\n\n### Editing Shipping & Currency Later\n\nThe order detail shows the same Shipping & Currency info, and while the order is still a **Draft** an **Edit** button appears next to it. Editing lets you change the Incoterm, Estimated Freight, and Quote Currency, and also set the **FX Rate** and **FX Rate Source** (for example, where the rate came from or the date you looked it up). Once the order leaves Draft, these become read-only.\n\n### FX Rate — Locked at Submit\n\nFor an order in another currency, the exchange rate used to convert the vendor's quote into your home currency is **locked when you submit** the order. This fixes the home-currency value at the moment you place the order, so later currency swings don't quietly change what the order is worth. The locked **FX Rate** and its **Source** are shown in the Shipping & Currency info on the order. If you need to fix the rate before submitting, edit the Draft as described above.\n\n### Below-Vendor-Minimum Warning\n\nIf the order total (lines plus estimated freight) falls under the vendor's minimum order amount, the order shows a **below vendor minimum** notice with that minimum. It's just a heads-up — it doesn't stop you from submitting — but it's a nudge to combine or add lines so you clear the vendor's minimum.\n\n### Freight Capture at Receipt\n\nEstimated freight is what you expected; **actual freight** is what the shipment really cost. You record it when the goods arrive. Receive Items has a **Shipping & Currency** section below the line quantities:\n\n- **Actual Freight** — the real freight charge for this delivery. It **starts at the order's estimated freight**, so if it matches the estimate you're one click away. Otherwise, replace it with the figure from the carrier invoice or packing slip.\n- **Freight Allocation Method** — how the freight cost is spread across the received lines for landed-cost purposes:\n  - **By Extended Value (default)** — allocate proportionally to each line's extended value (quantity times unit price). Higher-value lines absorb more freight.\n  - **By Quantity** — allocate proportionally to the units received on each line. Every unit carries the same freight share regardless of price.\n  - **Manual (per-line)** — you assign the freight split yourself, line by line.\n\n### Freight Variance\n\nWhen the actual freight you enter differs from the estimate, a **Variance** label appears next to the freight fields showing the percentage difference. Its color is a quick signal — calm when it's within roughly ±10%, cautionary in the middle, and stands out when the actual freight is well off the estimate (beyond about ±25%). It never stops you from receiving; it just flags deliveries where freight came in a lot higher or lower than planned, which helps when reviewing estimates and vendor performance.\n\n### Putting It Together\n\nA typical flow: pick the Incoterm and enter an estimated freight when you build the order → the exchange rate locks when you submit an order in another currency → when the shipment lands, open Receive Items, confirm or replace the actual freight, choose how to spread it, and save. The order now carries both the planned and the actual freight, spread across the right lines for an accurate landed cost.","sections":[]}"""
        });

