            Tags = """["purchase-orders","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Off-Price Prompt\n\nWhen you save an order, Forge checks each line's price against the price you've agreed with that vendor for that quantity. If any line's price is off by more than the set threshold, a single prompt appears for the whole order (not one per line). Each listed line shows the part, the agreed price (or 'no agreed price' when there isn't one), the price you entered, and how far off it is. For each line, you choose:\n\n- **Record as an exception (default)** — save this line at the price you entered, just this once. Your agreed pricing stays as it is. This is the default so your standing prices are never changed by accident.\n- **Update the agreed price** — save the entered price as the new agreed price for that vendor and quantity, effective today. Future orders then start from the new figure.\n\nAt the bottom: **Cancel** takes you back to the order; **Continue** applies your choices and goes on to submit the order.\n\n## Changing a Filled-In Price\n\nWhen you pick a part, its unit price fills in from the agreed price. Changing that filled-in price is limited:\n\n- **Who can do it** — only Admins and Managers can change a filled-in price. For everyone else it snaps back to the agreed price with a note that they don't have permission.\n- **Reason** — if you're allowed to change it, you're asked why. Leave the reason blank and the price snaps back; enter a reason and it's saved with the line.\n\nThe reason stays with the order so anyone reviewing it later can see why the price was changed. (Typing a price on a line you built from scratch, or nudging a price that wasn't the filled-in one, doesn't ask for a reason.)\n\n## AI Price Check\n\nWhen this is turned on for your install, you can ask for an AI review of a price change. Forge first works out, on its own, how the price compares to the agreed price and rates the risk — **Low** when it's on target, **High** when it's more than 25% off, and **Medium** in between — and drafts a short justification you can reuse. Then, if the AI assistant is available, it adds a couple of sentences flagging anything that looks off. If the assistant is offline, you still get the plain summary, so the review always works and never holds you up.\n\n## PO Barcode / QR Label\n\nEach order can carry a scannable code. The order detail shows its barcode as a QR code and lets you print a label. Scanning the printed code takes you straight back to the order — handy at receiving.\n\n## Orders on the Calendar\n\nExpected delivery dates show up on the calendar, so you can see at a glance what's due to arrive and when. Your install can also publish a read-only feed you subscribe to from an outside calendar app — it only shares these dates outward and doesn't accept anything back.\n\n## Draft Auto-Save\n\nWhile you're filling in a new or edited order, Forge quietly saves your progress. If you get interrupted, log out, or come back later, your in-progress work is waiting for you. It clears once you save, discard it, or leave it long enough to expire. Think of it as a safety net for line entry — not a replacement for saving the order.","sections":[]}"""
